essor|annotationProcessor|processor|maven-compiler|Static metamodel|generator' | head -120\",\"timeout\":60}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2526, "output": 118, "cacheRead": 20992, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 23636, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781872227930, "responseId": "resp_0049607bdd79438a016a35366479648195b539809db994bfcd"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_GZYLhP5ezre5in9hBOuFNwHN|fc_0049607bdd79438a016a3536678d2c8195a24d9ebbc22f2068", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "7:<meta name=\"generator\" content=\"Asciidoctor 2.0.23\">\n834:<li><a href=\"#generator\">7. Compile-time tooling</a>\n836:<li><a href=\"#static-metamodel\">7.1. The static metamodel</a></li>\n838:<li><a href=\"#generated-named-queries\">7.3. Named queries and Hibernate Processor</a></li>\n882:<li><a href=\"#user-defined-generators\">9.7. User-defined generators</a></li>\n1292:    <span class=\"c1\">// Hibernate Processor</span>\n1293:    <span class=\"n\">annotationProcessor</span> <span class=\"s1\">'org.hibernate.orm:hibernate-processor:7.2.19.Final'</span>\n1731:Indeed, since we included <a href=\"#metamodel-generator\">Hibernate Processor</a> in our <a href=\"#build-gradle\">Gradle build</a>, the query can even be validated at <em>compile time</em>.</p>\n1794:<p>Fortunately, there&#8217;s now a great solution to both problems. Hibernate Processor is able to fill in the implementation of such query methods for us.\n1795:This facility is the topic of <a href=\"#generator\">a whole chapter of this introduction</a>, so for now we&#8217;ll just leave you with one simple example.</p>\n1811:<p>Then Hibernate Processor automatically produces an implementation of the method annotated <code>@HQL</code> in a class named <code>Queries_</code>.\n1853:<p>The <code>Queries</code> interface is now considered a <em>repository</em>, and we may use CDI to inject the repository implementation generated by Hibernate Processor.\n1881:<p>The <a href=\"https://jakarta.ee/specifications/data/1.0/jakarta-data-1.0\">Jakarta Data specification</a> now formalizes this approach using standard annotations, and our implementation of this specification, Hibernate Data Repositories, is built into <a href=\"#generator\">Hibernate Processor</a>.\n2119:<p>using Hibernate Processor to improve compile-time type-safety,</p>\n2308:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\">The <a href=\"https://hibernate.org/orm/tooling/\">Hibernate Processor</a>, especially if you&#8217;re using Jakarta Data or the JPA criteria query API</p></td>\n2309:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\"><code>org.hibernate.orm:hibernate-processor</code></p></td>\n3565:<p>The <code>@SequenceGenerator</code> and <code>@TableGenerator</code> annotations allow further control over <code>SEQUENCE</code> and <code>TABLE</code> generation respectively.</p>\n3568:<p>Consider this sequence generator:</p>\n3572:<pre class=\"rouge highlight\"><code data-lang=\"java\"><span class=\"nd\">@SequenceGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">name</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s\">\"bookSeq\"</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">sequenceName</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s\">\"seq_book\"</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">initialValue</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">allocationSize</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"o\">)</span></code></pre>\n3597:But if you&#8217;re working with a database schema managed outside Hibernate, make sure the <code>initialValue</code> and <code>allocationSize</code> members of <code>@SequenceGenerator</code> match the <code>start with</code> and <code>increment</code> specified in the DDL.</p>\n3604:<p>Any identifier attribute may now make use of the generator named <code>bookSeq</code>:</p>\n3609:<span class=\"nd\">@GeneratedValue</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">generator</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s\">\"bookSeq\"</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>  <span class=\"c1\">// reference to generator defined elsewhere</span>\n3614:<p>Actually, it&#8217;s extremely common to place the <code>@SequenceGenerator</code> annotation on the <code>@Id</code> attribute that makes use of it:</p>\n3619:<span class=\"nd\">@GeneratedValue</span>  <span class=\"c1\">// uses the generator defined below</span>\n3620:<span class=\"nd\">@SequenceGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">sequenceName</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s\">\"seq_book\"</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">initialValue</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">allocationSize</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n3625:<p>In this case, the <code>name</code> of the <code>@SequenceGenerator</code> should not be specified.</p>\n3628:<p>We may even place a <code>@SequenceGenerator</code> or <code>@TableGenerator</code> annotation at the package level:</p>\n3632:<pre class=\"rouge highlight\"><code data-lang=\"java\"><span class=\"nd\">@SequenceGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">sequenceName</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s\">\"id_sequence\"</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">initialValue</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">allocationSize</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n3633:<span class=\"nd\">@TableGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">table</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s\">\"id_table\"</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">initialValue</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"mi\">5</span><span class=\"o\">,</span> <span class=\"n\">allocationSize</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n3638:<p>Then any entity in this package which specifies <code>strategy=SEQUENCE</code> or <code>strategy=TABLE</code> without also explicitly specifying a generator <code>name</code> will be assigned a generator based on the package-level annotation.</p>\n3643:<span class=\"nd\">@GeneratedValue</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">strategy</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"no\">SEQUENCE</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>  <span class=\"c1\">// uses the sequence generator defined at the package level</span>\n3651:Since custom id generation is a rather common requirement, Hibernate provides a very carefully-designed framework for user-defined <code>Generator</code>s, which we&#8217;ll discuss in <a href=\"#user-defined-generators\">User-defined generators</a>.</p>\n3813:<p>If the datetime value should be generated by the database, the <code>@Version</code> annotation may be used in conjunction with a <a href=\"#user-defined-generators\">generator annotation</a>, for example:</p>\n5058:Thankfully, the <a href=\"#metamodel-generator\">Hibernate Processor</a> gives us a way to make it a\n5909:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\"><code>@SequenceGenerator</code></p></td>\n5910:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\">Define an id generator backed by a database sequence</p></td>\n5914:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\"><code>@TableGenerator</code></p></td>\n5919:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\"><code>@IdGeneratorType</code></p></td>\n5920:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\">Declare an annotation that associates a custom <code>Generator</code> with each <code>@Id</code> attribute it annotates</p></td>\n5925:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\">Declare an annotation that associates a custom <code>Generator</code> with each <code>@Basic</code> attribute it annotates</p></td>\n8619:<p>In the code examples above, The classes <code>Book_</code> and <code>Author_</code> are generated by <a href=\"#metamodel-generator\">Hibernate Processor</a>, as we saw earlier.\n8787:<p>Notice that this code fragment is completely typesafe, again thanks to <a href=\"#metamodel-generator\">Hibernate Processor</a>.</p>\n9517:<p>For example, we may pass a <a href=\"#static-metamodel\">static metamodel</a> reference to <code>setParameter()</code>.</p>\n9668:<p>Here, as before, the classes <code>Book_</code> and <code>Author_</code> are generated by <a href=\"#metamodel-generator\">Hibernate Processor</a>.</p>\n9939:<p><em>does</em> make use of the JPA <a href=\"#metamodel-generator\">static metamodel</a> for type safety,</p>\n10501:<p>Here, <code>BookQueries_._10BooksByTitle_</code> is an element of the JPA static metamodel of type <code>TypedQueryReference&lt;Book&gt;</code>, generated by Hibernate Processor.</p>\n10509:In <a href=\"#organizing-persistence\">Organizing persistence logic</a>, we mentioned that the Hibernate Processor can do that for us, with the help of the <code>@CheckHQL</code> annotation, and we presented that as a reason to use <code>@NamedQuery</code>.</p>\n10527:<p>We&#8217;re going to learn more about Hibernate Processor in the next chapter.</p>\n10533:<h2 id=\"generator\"><a class=\"anchor\" href=\"#generator\"></a>7. Compile-time tooling</h2>\n10536:<p>The <em>static metamodel generator</em> is a standard part of JPA.\n10537:We&#8217;ve actually already seen its handiwork in the code examples <a href=\"#main-hibernate\">earlier</a>: it&#8217;s the author of the class <code>Book_</code>, which contains the static metamodel of the <a href=\"#book\">entity class</a> <code>Book</code>.</p>\n10540:<p>Hibernate comes with an annotation processor which does much more than just this.\n10559:<div id=\"metamodel-generator\" class=\"sidebarblock\">\n10561:<div class=\"title\">Hibernate Processor</div>\n10563:<p><a href=\"https://hibernate.org/orm/processor/\">Hibernate Processor</a>, the annotation processor formerly known as the Metamodel Generator, began its life as a code generator for what JPA calls a <a href=\"https://jakarta.ee/specifications/persistence/3.2/jakarta-persistence-spec-3.2#a6072\"><em>static metamodel</em></a>.\n10569:Back when Java&#8217;s annotation processing API was brand spankin' new, the static metamodel for JPA was proposed by Gavin King for inclusion in JPA 2.0, as a way to achieve type safety in the nascent criteria query API.\n10571:Tools did not, at the time, feature robust support for annotation processors.\n10577:<p>But time has been kind to the static metamodel.\n10580:The static metamodel itself is undeniably useful and elegant.</p>\n10584:Since Hibernate 6.3 the Processor has started taking on a much bigger role.\n10588:<p>Now, you still don&#8217;t have to use the Hibernate Processor with Hibernate—the APIs we just mentioned still also accept plain strings—but we find that it works well with Gradle and integrates smoothly with our IDE, and the advantage in type-safety is compelling.</p>\n10600:<p>We&#8217;ve already seen how to set up the annotation processor in the <a href=\"#hello-hibernate\">Gradle build</a> we saw earlier.\n10601:For more details on how to integrate the Hibernate Processor, check out the <a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/userguide/html_single/Hibernate_User_Guide.html#tooling-modelgen\">Static Metamodel Generator</a> section in the User Guide.</p>\n10608:<h3 id=\"static-metamodel\"><a class=\"anchor\" href=\"#static-metamodel\"></a>7.1. The static metamodel</h3>\n10610:<p>We&#8217;ve already seen several ways to use the JPA static metamodel.\n10705:<p>Hibernate Processor allows <em>statically-typed</em> access to elements of the JPA <code>Metamodel</code>. But the <code>Metamodel</code> is also accessible in a \"reflective\" way, via the <code>EntityManagerFactory</code>.</p>\n10722:<p>The JPA static metamodel for an entity also contains members representing the named queries and named entity graphs declared by <code>@NamedQuery</code>, <code>@NamedNativeQuery</code>, and <code>@NamedEntityGraph</code> annotations of the entity class.</p>\n10778:<p>Actually, Hibernate Processor doesn&#8217;t require that such annotations be applied to the entity class itself, as we <a href=\"#organizing-persistence\">already saw earlier</a>.</p>\n10786:So now let&#8217;s see what else Hibernate Processor can do for us.</p>\n10792:<p>Automatic generation of <em>finder methods</em> and <em>query methods</em> is a relatively new feature of Hibernate Processor&#8212;&#8203;originally introduced as an experiment&#8212;&#8203;which ultimately grew into a whole new way to use Hibernate.</p>\n10824:<p>Back in <a href=\"#organizing-persistence\">Organizing persistence logic</a>, we walked you through a few different ways to organize your code with the help of Hibernate Processor.\n10827:Hibernate Processor is perfectly happy to generate <code>static</code> implementations of <code>@HQL</code>, <code>@SQL</code>, and <code>@Find</code> methods, eliminating the need to inject or instantiate a repository object.</p>\n10831:<div class=\"title\">Hibernate Processor and Jakarta Data</div>\n10855:Hibernate Processor is not currently able to generate finder methods and query methods for entities declared completely in XML, and it&#8217;s not able to validate HQL which queries such entities.\n10856:(On the other hand, the <a href=\"#object-relational-mapping\">O/R mappings</a> may be specified in XML, since they&#8217;re not needed by the Processor.)</p>\n10867:<h3 id=\"generated-named-queries\"><a class=\"anchor\" href=\"#generated-named-queries\"></a>7.3. Named queries and Hibernate Processor</h3>\n10884:<p>Now the Processor adds the following method declaration to the metamodel class <code>Book_</code>.</p>\n10917:In the case we just saw, Hibernate Processor does a reasonable job of inferring the query return type and parameter types, but we&#8217;re often going to need a bit more control.</p>\n10960:<p>Notice that the signature differs just slightly from the one we wrote down in the <code>Queries</code> interface: the Processor has prepended a parameter accepting <code>EntityManager</code> to the parameter list.</p>\n10974:<p>Hibernate Processor defaults to using <code>EntityManager</code> as the session type, but other types are allowed:</p>\n10991:Hibernate Processor verifies that the parameters of our abstract method declaration match the parameters of the HQL query, for example:</p>\n11005:Hibernate Processor determines this by inspecting the annotations of the entity classes at compile time.</p>\n11023:In this case there&#8217;s a lot less the Processor can do to check that the query is legal and well-typed.</p>\n11058:<p>Now Hibernate Processor does something a bit different:</p>\n11645:The <a href=\"https://github.com/hibernate/query-validator/\">Query Validator</a> is a separate annotation processor that&#8217;s capable of type-checking HQL strings, not only in annotations, but even when they occur as arguments to <code>createQuery()</code>, <code>createSelectionQuery()</code>, or <code>createMutationQuery()</code>. It&#8217;s even able to check calls to <code>setParameter()</code>, with some restrictions.</p>\n11658:<p>Unlike Hibernate Processor, which is a completely bog-standard Java annotation processor based on only standard Java APIs, the Query Validator makes use of internal compiler APIs in <code>javac</code> and <code>ecj</code>. This means it can&#8217;t be guaranteed to work in every Java compiler. The current release is known to work in JDK 11 and above, though JDK 15 or above is preferred.</p>\n13942:<p>Here, as usual, <code>example_.BY_REGION</code> is generated by Hibernate Processor, and is just a constant with the value <code>\"ByRegion\"</code>.</p>\n14678:<h3 id=\"user-defined-generators\"><a class=\"anchor\" href=\"#user-defined-generators\"></a>9.7. User-defined generators</h3>\n14685:<p>the <a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/javadocs/org/hibernate/generator/Generator.html\"><code>Generator</code></a> hierarchy of interfaces in the package <code>org.hibernate.generator</code> lets you define new generators, and</p>\n14688:<p>the <a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/javadocs/org/hibernate/annotations/IdGeneratorType.html\"><code>@IdGeneratorType</code></a> meta-annotation from the package <code>org.hibernate.annotations</code> lets you write an annotation which associates a <code>Generator</code> type with identifier attributes.</p>\n14693:<p>Furthermore, the <a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/javadocs/org/hibernate/annotations/ValueGenerationType.html\"><code>@ValueGenerationType</code></a> meta-annotation lets you write an annotation which associates a <code>Generator</code> type with a non-<code>@Id</code> attribute.</p>\n14703:<p>These APIs were new in Hibernate 6, and supersede the classic <code>IdentifierGenerator</code> interface and <code>@GenericGenerator</code> annotation from older versions of Hibernate.\n14704:However, the older APIs are still available and custom <code>IdentifierGenerator</code>s written for older versions of Hibernate continue to work in Hibernate 7.</p>\n14711:<p>Hibernate has a range of built-in generators which are defined in terms of this new framework.</p>\n14714:<caption class=\"title\">Table 9.4: Built-in generators</caption>\n14754:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\"><a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/javadocs/org/hibernate/annotations/UuidGenerator.html\"><code>@UuidGenerator</code></a></p></td>\n14755:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\"><code>UuidGenerator</code></p></td>\n14756:<td class=\"tableblock halign-left valign-top\"><p class=\"tableblock\">A more flexible generator for RFC 4122 UUIDs</p></td>\n14764:<p>As an example, let&#8217;s look at how <a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/javadocs/org/hibernate/annotations/UuidGenerator.html\"><code>@UuidGenerator</code></a> is defined:</p>\n14768:<pre class=\"rouge highlight\"><code data-lang=\"java\"><span class=\"nd\">@IdGeneratorType</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">org</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">hibernate</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">id</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">uuid</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">UuidGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">class</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n14769:<span class=\"nd\">@ValueGenerationType</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">generatedBy</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">org</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">hibernate</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">id</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">uuid</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">UuidGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">class</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n14772:<span class=\"kd\">public</span> <span class=\"nd\">@interface</span> <span class=\"nc\">UuidGenerator</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span> <span class=\"o\">...</span> <span class=\"o\">}</span></code></pre>\n14776:<p><code>@UuidGenerator</code> is meta-annotated both <code>@IdGeneratorType</code> and <code>@ValueGenerationType</code> because it may be used to generate both ids and values of regular attributes.\n14777:Either way, <a href=\"https://docs.hibernate.org/orm/7.2/javadocs/org/hibernate/id/uuid/UuidGenerator.html\">this <code>Generator</code> class</a> does the hard work:</p>\n14781:<pre class=\"rouge highlight\"><code data-lang=\"java\"><span class=\"kd\">public</span> <span class=\"kd\">class</span> <span class=\"nc\">UuidGenerator</span>\n14782:        <span class=\"c1\">// this generator produced values before SQL is executed</span>\n14783:        <span class=\"kd\">implements</span> <span class=\"nc\">BeforeExecutionGenerator</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span>\n14785:    <span class=\"c1\">// constructors accept an instance of the @UuidGenerator</span>\n14786:    <span class=\"c1\">// annotation, allowing the generator to be \"configured\"</span>\n14788:    <span class=\"c1\">// called to create an id generator</span>\n14789:    <span class=\"kd\">public</span> <span class=\"nf\">UuidGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">(</span>\n14790:            <span class=\"n\">org</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">hibernate</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">annotations</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">UuidGenerator</span> <span class=\"n\">config</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n14792:            <span class=\"nc\">GeneratorCreationContext</span> <span class=\"n\">creationContext</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span>\n14796:    <span class=\"c1\">// called to create a generator for a regular attribute</span>\n14797:    <span class=\"kd\">public</span> <span class=\"nf\">UuidGenerator</span><span class=\"o\">(</span>\n14798:            <span class=\"n\">org</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">hibernate</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">annotations</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">UuidGenerator</span> <span class=\"n\">config</span><span class=\"o\">,</span>\n14800:            <span class=\"nc\">GeneratorCreationContext</span> <span class=\"n\">creationContext</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span>\n14815:        <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"n\">valueTransformer</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">transform</span><span class=\"o\">(</span> <span class=\"n\">generator</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"na\">generateUuid</span><span class=\"o\">(</span> <span class=\"n\">session</span> <span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">);</span>\n14821:<p>You can find out more about custom generators from the Javadoc for <code>@IdGeneratorType</code> and for <code>org.hibernate.generator</code>.</p>\n15787:<p>Here, once again, <code>Book_.PROFILE_EAGER_BOOK</code> is generated by Hibernate Processor, and is just a constant with the value <code>\"EagerBook\"</code>.</p>\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1781872233309}]}
